    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "**Key insight:** After industry-median imputation, 39,244 postings have usable salary values, representing 54.15% of the cleaned dataset. However, 33,232 postings still have missing salary values, so salary-based results should be interpreted as applying to the salary-available portion of the dataset rather than the full job market.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 4. Salary Missingness Across Job Characteristics\n",
        "\n",
        "Why this analysis was chosen:  \n",
        "Salary availability may not be random. This section checks whether salary missingness differs across AI-related status, remote-work type, state, and industry. These patterns are important because uneven missingness can affect later salary interpretation."
      ],
      "id": "d7c32a18"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "message": false
      },
      "source": [
        "#| echo: false\n",
        "#| warning: false\n",
        "\n",
        "salary_missing_by_ai = spark.sql(\"\"\"\n",
        "SELECT\n",
        "    career_type,\n",
        "    COUNT(DISTINCT id) AS total_postings,\n",
        "    COUNT(DISTINCT CASE\n",
        "        WHEN salary IS NOT NULL AND salary > 0\n",
        "        THEN id\n",
        "    END) AS salary_available,\n",
        "    COUNT(DISTINCT CASE\n",
        "        WHEN salary IS NULL OR salary <= 0\n",
        "        THEN id\n",
        "    END) AS salary_missing,\n",
        "    ROUND(\n",
        "        COUNT(DISTINCT CASE\n",
        "            WHEN salary IS NULL OR salary <= 0\n",
        "            THEN id\n",
        "        END) / COUNT(DISTINCT id) * 100,\n",
        "        2\n",
        "    ) AS missing_salary_percent\n",
        "FROM jobs_with_ai\n",
        "GROUP BY career_type\n",
        "ORDER BY missing_salary_percent DESC\n",
        "\"\"\").toPandas()\n",
        "\n",
        "display(style_table(salary_missing_by_ai, {\n",
        "    \"total_postings\": \"{:,.0f}\",\n",
        "    \"salary_available\": \"{:,.0f}\",\n",
        "    \"salary_missing\": \"{:,.0f}\",\n",
        "    \"missing_salary_percent\": \"{:.2f}%\"\n",
        "}))\n",
        "\n",
        "salary_missing_by_remote = spark.sql(\"\"\"\n",
        "SELECT\n",
        "    COALESCE(remote_type_name, 'Unknown') AS remote_type,\n",
        "    COUNT(DISTINCT id) AS total_postings,\n",
        "    COUNT(DISTINCT CASE\n",
        "        WHEN salary IS NOT NULL AND salary > 0\n",
        "        THEN id\n",
        "    END) AS salary_available,\n",
        "    COUNT(DISTINCT CASE\n",
        "        WHEN salary IS NULL OR salary <= 0\n",
        "        THEN id\n",
        "    END) AS salary_missing,\n",
        "    ROUND(\n",
        "        COUNT(DISTINCT CASE\n",
        "            WHEN salary IS NULL OR salary <= 0\n",
        "            THEN id\n",
        "        END) / COUNT(DISTINCT id) * 100,\n",
        "        2\n",
        "    ) AS missing_salary_percent\n",
        "FROM job_postings\n",
        "GROUP BY COALESCE(remote_type_name, 'Unknown')\n",
        "ORDER BY missing_salary_percent DESC\n",
        "\"\"\").toPandas()\n",
        "\n",
        "display(style_table(salary_missing_by_remote, {\n",
        "    \"total_postings\": \"{:,.0f}\",\n",
        "    \"salary_available\": \"{:,.0f}\",\n",
        "    \"salary_missing\": \"{:,.0f}\",\n",
        "    \"missing_salary_percent\": \"{:.2f}%\"\n",
        "}))\n",
        "\n",
        "salary_missing_by_state = spark.sql(\"\"\"\n",
        "SELECT\n",
        "    l.state_name,\n",
        "    COUNT(DISTINCT j.id) AS total_postings,\n",
        "    COUNT(DISTINCT CASE\n",
        "        WHEN j.salary IS NOT NULL AND j.salary > 0\n",
        "        THEN j.id\n",
        "    END) AS salary_available,\n",
        "    COUNT(DISTINCT CASE\n",
        "        WHEN j.salary IS NULL OR j.salary <= 0\n",
        "        THEN j.id\n",
        "    END) AS salary_missing,\n",
        "    ROUND(\n",
        "        COUNT(DISTINCT CASE\n",
        "            WHEN j.salary IS NULL OR j.salary <= 0\n",
        "            THEN j.id\n",
        "        END) / COUNT(DISTINCT j.id) * 100,\n",
        "        2\n",
        "    ) AS missing_salary_percent\n",
        "FROM job_postings j\n",
        "LEFT JOIN locations l\n",
        "    ON j.location_id = l.location_id\n",
        "WHERE l.state_name IS NOT NULL\n",
        "GROUP BY l.state_name\n",
        "HAVING COUNT(DISTINCT j.id) >= 100\n",
        "ORDER BY missing_salary_percent DESC\n",
        "LIMIT 10\n",
        "\"\"\").toPandas()\n",
        "\n",
        "display(style_table(salary_missing_by_state, {\n",
        "    \"total_postings\": \"{:,.0f}\",\n",
        "    \"salary_available\": \"{:,.0f}\",\n",
        "    \"salary_missing\": \"{:,.0f}\",\n",
        "    \"missing_salary_percent\": \"{:.2f}%\"\n",
        "}))"
      ],
      "id": "cd6dd4d8",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "**Key insight:** Salary missingness is not evenly distributed across job characteristics. AI-related postings have a higher missing salary rate than non-AI postings, and missingness also varies by remote-work category and state. This suggests that salary availability may be affected by job type, location, and posting characteristics, which should be considered when interpreting later salary results.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 5. Salary Distribution in the Dataset\n",
        "\n",
        "Why this visualization was chosen:  \n",
        "Salary is the main compensation variable in this project. A histogram helps show whether salary values are concentrated in a common range or affected by high-end outliers."
      ],
      "id": "ab553ee1"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
