        "\n",
        "## 12. EDA Summary and Implications for Later Analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "The exploratory analysis shows that the cleaned dataset provides broad job-market coverage, with 72,476 unique job postings across thousands of companies, locations, industries, occupations, and skills. However, salary-based analysis is limited to the subset of postings with usable salary information. After salary preparation and industry-median imputation, 39,244 postings, or 54.15% of the dataset, have usable salary values, while 33,232 postings remain missing salary.\n",
        "\n",
        "The missing salary pattern is not fully random. Salary missingness varies by AI-related status, remote-work type, and state, meaning later salary comparisons should be interpreted with this limitation in mind. The EDA also shows that salary values are concentrated in a middle range but include a smaller high-salary tail, so later modeling should consider both typical prediction error and the effect of high-salary outliers.\n",
        "\n",
        "Several job characteristics appear important for later analysis. Salary differs across education levels and occupation categories, while job postings are geographically concentrated in high-volume states such as Texas and California. The occupation and skill results show that the dataset contains multiple career paths, including Data Analyst, ERP, Enterprise Architect, Oracle, SAP, BI, and business analyst roles. Skills also combine technical tools, such as SQL, Python, Excel, Power BI, SAP, and Business Intelligence, with business-facing skills such as Communication, Management, Leadership, and Project Management.\n",
        "\n",
        "Overall, the EDA suggests that later salary analysis and predictive modeling should account for occupation, education, location, remote-work status, and skills, while also acknowledging data-quality limitations such as the large [None] remote-work category and the large Unclassified Industry category.\n",
        "\n",
